1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Everybody in the conference room now, please. Thank you.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Time is money.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Do you need anything?

4
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,000
No.

5
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:11,000
Should I get water or donuts?

6
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:12,000
No.

7
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Come on, let's go. Take a seat.

8
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:18,000
What's going on, Michael?

9
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:22,000
I want somebody to give me the name of one of our biggest competitors.

10
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Office Depot.

11
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Good. Yes, that will work.

12
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Alright, now I need a plural noun.

13
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Apparently Michael has come up with a Dunder Mifflin madlib, and he's making us play it with him.

14
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:39,000
We are so happy.

15
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,000
No, I'd like to choose a different adjective.

16
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:45,000
How about a location?

17
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,000
The planet Capricum.

18
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Where the hell is that?

19
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,000
It's from Battle Circle, Capricum.

20
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Okay, alright.

21
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,000
I am going back to my desk now.

22
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:54,000
No, no, no, not until you give me an adjective.

23
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,000
Annoying.

24
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:58,000
We already have that, so...

25
00:00:58,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Frustrating.

26
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,000
No, Toby, damn it, come on. We already have that. I need something fun.

27
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Something like fat or smelly or pukey.

28
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Pukey.

29
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Pukey's good.

30
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Okay.

31
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Pukey.

32
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Now I need a noun.

33
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:12,000
Ass.

34
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Good.

35
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Thank you, Phyllis. That wasn't so hard.

36
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Alright, here we go.

37
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Office Depot is an annoying store.

38
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:25,000
One day, Creed went there to buy paper.

39
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:29,000
And he ran into irritating silos.

40
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Yeah, get him, Creed.

41
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
One of them was named Michael Scott.

42
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,000
And he was an...

43
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Oh, damn it. Okay.

44
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Okay, okay, we're... Okay, we're starting over.

45
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Tonight, the Scranton Business Park is having casino night.

46
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:59,000
And we are converting our warehouse into a full-blown gambling hall.

47
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:03,000
And I know that the only way to get there is to buy paper.

48
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:16,000
But, I think, if you're going to get paper, you need to have a good

49
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:17,000
casino night.

50
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And we are converting our warehouse into a full-blown gambling hall.

51
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
And I know it's illegal in Pennsylvania, but it's for charity.

52
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:27,000
And I consider myself a great philanderer.

53
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:31,000
It's just, it's nice to know, at the end of the day, I can look in the mirror and say,

54
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Michael, because of you, some little kid in the Congo has a belly full of rice this evening.

55
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Just... makes you feel good.

56
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Excuse me, how long is it that you wait for a table for two?

57
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:59,000
I would never, ever serve you. Not in a million billion years.

58
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,000
It's a nice tux.

59
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:03,000
I know. It belonged to my grandfather.

60
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,000
He was buried in it, so... family heirloom.

61
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
So what's the deal? We gotta pay for our own drinks? That's lame.

62
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,000
Come on, it'll be fun. And besides, I'm a roulette expert.

63
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:21,000
Impossible. Roulette is not a game of skill, it is a game of chance.

64
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:23,000
I could always kind of win at roulette.

65
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Oh, really? How would you do that?

66
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Mind control.

67
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,000
You can't be serious.

68
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:34,000
Are you serious?

69
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:40,000
Ever since I was a little kid, like eight or nine, I could sort of control things with my mind.

70
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
I don't believe you. Continue.

71
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
It was just little things, you know? Like I could make something shake, or I could make a marble fall off the counter.

72
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
You know, just little things.

73
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:52,000
That's ridiculous.

74
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:57,000
You know what? Uh, why don't you move that coat rack?

75
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Excuse me, everyone. Attention in the office, please.

76
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,000
Jim is about to prove his telekinetic powers, and he needs absolute silence.

77
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:07,000
Go ahead.

78
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,000
Okay, I'll try.

79
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Oh my god.

80
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,000
I try not to think of it as lagging behind. It's more of a David and Goliath thing.

81
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Well, the fact of the matter is that your branch is currently number four of the five branches that I oversee.

82
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Top 80 percent.

83
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Michael?

84
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Yep?

85
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,000
You know that I'm very serious here.

86
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Jan, listen, I promise I will kick it up a notch. Bam!

87
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,000
What?

88
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Emeril. Oh, actually, while I have you, not that I have you or have ever had you, but we're having our casino night tonight, and I think everyone would love to see their fearless leader here.

89
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
I thought that you were their fearless leader.

90
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
I am, but you are the Eva Perone to my Cesar Chavez.

91
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:28,000
Oh, come on. Come on. It'd be fun. I can hear it in your voice. You need a break.

92
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:31,000
Goodbye, Michael.

93
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:42,000
Jan and I understand each other. The romancing is sort of on hold for the time being, but we remain good friends. Good friends with privileges. Not now, someday.

94
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:50,000
I don't believe that Jim moved that coat rack.

95
00:05:50,000 --> 00:06:04,000
But if he did, he has an obligation to use his gift wisely. With great power comes great responsibility. They could do a cross-section of his brain to find out more, but I don't think it's true, though.

96
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:09,000
Okay, everybody. Tonight's event is to benefit the Boy Scouts of America.

97
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
Again. We do that every year.

98
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Well, they need our money. They don't have cookies like the Girl Scouts.

99
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:17,000
It'd be nice to do something for people who are actually suffering.

100
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Well, Oscar, if you don't like it, then you should concentrate on winning, because the person at the end of the evening with the highest chip can't even get a good shot.
